the onset of the current massive exodus of refugees, which started in August 2015 and has led to a socio-political conflict and destabilisation of the country, as well as the shutting down of the refugee camps and return of tens of thousands of Burundians to their country. According to the Ministry of Human Rights and Humanitarian Action of Burundi, around 107,300 refugees had returned from all refugee camps in eastern provinces of Rwanda and over the last year, close to 60,000 refugees have returned to Burundi.

Although a majority of Burundi are living in a largely free society, they are exposed to deadly diseases, gender-based violence, crime, etc. Furthermore, unrestricted and uncensored information is lacking in the country. The high level of risk of social unrest may be combated by preventing poliovirus transmission/elimination. Polio is a crippling and potentially fatal infectious disease, caused by the poliovirus.

The greatest obstacle for polio eradication that the country is facing, is the transportation situation, due to poor infrastructure. Transportation of immunization materials is easier through UNICEF and Partners’ vehicles, which is a great asset for the concurrent measles
